African swine fever, Cote d'Ivoire
----------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 27 Aug 2014 from Dre Diarra Cisse, [Director, Veterinary Services, Ministry of Animal Resources and Fisheries], Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 1 Jun 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 19 Aug 2014
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: December 1996
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: African swine fever [ASF] virus
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: San Pedro, San Pedro, San Pedro, San Pedro [Bas-Sassandra District]
Date of start of the outbreak: 1 Jun 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed/ Slaughtered
Swine/ 1500 / 600 / 600 / 0 / 0
Affected population: High mortality in swine without prodromes. Number of cases reached 600 and mortality still continues to increase. Several missions were sent to the field.

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Swine / 40 / 40 / 100 / 40
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: swill feeding

Control measures
Measures applied: no vaccination; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: movement control inside the country

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
National Laboratory for Support to Agricultural Development (LACANA) (national laboratory) / Swine / polymerase chain reaction PCR / 18 Aug 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

